    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th scope="row">2</th>
      <td>PCOD has no serious complications.</td>
      <td>Type 2 diabetes, high blood pressure, heart disease, and advanced endometrial cancer are serious complications associated with PCOS.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th scope="row">3</th>
      <td >PCOD is a medical condition where the women’s ovaries produce immature or partially impure eggs, which transform into cysts.</td>
      <td>PCOS is a more severe condition where the ovaries produce a high quantity of male hormones, resulting in excess cyst formation.</td>
    </tr>
      <tr>
      <th scope="row">4</th>
      <td >PCOD doesn’t have severe complications and can be healed with the right diet plan.</td>
      <td>While polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) cannot be cured, the symptoms can be controlled through lifestyle changes and medicines.</td>
